..TEXT:
We can begin to understand that Dante has constructed this
terrace in a way that is much different from that in which he
structured the Circle of Avarice and Prodigality in ^Inferno~.  There
the two sins are treated, at least approximately, as equals, each of
them sharing literally half the realm.  Here it would seem (one cannot
be certain) that there is no set place for the penitent prodigal nor
any exemplary figures that refer directly to their sin.  In fact, this
is the Terrace of Avarice on which prodigals seem to be gathered, too.
Since the only one we know of -- and he refers to no others in his
condition -- is Statius, we have no way of knowing or guessing how many
others there are like him, or even whether there are any others at all.
